channel.description:
In this tutorial I'm going to explain the following subjects:
[b]
1 - Creating the variables for quest-progress saving, and saving them to the character's save file
2 - NpcDialogues. Stringing together stories, and handeling choices
3 - Counting specific NPC kills
4 - Quest rewards[/b]

[b]Difficulty:[/b]  4/10.
- This tutorial contains quite a bit of copy-pasting, but also requires some creativity from the reader.

[b]Files used:[/b] Client.java, NpcHandler.java, ClickingMost.java, Player.java

[b]Base used:[/b] Delta cleaned, but I'm guessing it should also work on different bases.


Alright, let's begin.



[b]Creating the variables for quest progress saving[/b]

An important aspect of questmaking, is being able to save the progress the player has made. Nobody want's to start a quest all over again after they have logged out, or have gotten disconnected.

To start off, you will need to declare these two variables in Player.java:
[code=java]public int quest1; // This variable will contain what queststage the player is currently at
public int rats; // This is optional. This variable will contain what amount of rats the player has killed[/code]

[b]NOTE:[/b]
Now in my quest, the player had to kill a certain amount of rats. Ofcourse, you can use a different name for this variable if you are not going to use rats in your quest, but I'm going to use this variable for the rest of the tutorial.

Ok, so you have declared the two variables. Great, now what?
Well, the variables you have added, are currently not getting saved when the player logs out. Let's change this.


[b]Actually saving the quest progress[/b]

Open up Client.java, and search for this:
[code=java]else if (token.equals("character-rights"))[/code]

You should see something like this:

[code=java]else if (token.equals("character-rights")) {
						playerRights = Integer.parseInt(token2);
					}[/code]

After the [b]}[/b], add this:

[code=java]else if (token.equals("character-quest1")) {
	quest1 = Integer.parseInt(token2);
} else if (token.equals("character-rats")) {
	rats = Integer.parseInt(token2);
}[/code]

This will load the values of character-quest1 and rats, from the player's save file, into the variables quest1 and rats.
Great, so you can now load variables from the character's save file. Now it's time for the saving itself.

Still, in Client.java, search for:
[code=java]characterfile.write(Integer.toString(playerRights)[/code]

You should find this:
[code=java]
characterfile.write("character-rights = ", 0, 19);
characterfile.write(Integer.toString(playerRights), 0, Integer.toString(playerRights).length());
characterfile.newLine();
[/code]

After the [b]characterfile.newLine();[/b], add this code:
[code=java]
characterfile.write("character-quest1 = ", 0, 19);
characterfile.write(Integer.toString(quest1), 0, Integer.toString(quest1).length());
characterfile.newLine();
characterfile.write("character-rats = ", 0, 17);
characterfile.write(Integer.toString(rats), 0, Integer.toString(rats).length());
characterfile.newLine();[/code]

Now, you are probably wondering (or not), what the 19 and 17 in this code mean.
This number represents the amount of characters that has to written in the character's save file.
If you count the amount of characters (spaces are also characters), between the "'s of
[code=java]"character-quest1 = "[/code]
you will see there are 19 characters. In [b]characters-rats = [/b]  are 17 characters. Hence the 19 and 17.

[b]This is very important! If you do not set these numbers right, the string will not get written in the character's save file. So make sure you add the right number![/b]

Phew! That was pretty hard, wasn't it?  Well you can relax for now, now it's time for something a bit easier.




[b]NpcDialogues[/b]

Now, before we can continue, you must choose the NPC you want to use as the quest starter.
We will need his NpcID to display his face in the dialogues, so make sure you have one in mind.
For this tutorial, I have picked [b]Sir Vyvin[/b], his NpcID is [b]605[/b].


To be able to talk to an NPC, we must first create some dialogues.

In Client.java, search for the folowing method:
[code=java]public void UpdateNPCChat() {[/code]

This is the method that handles all the NpcDialogues. It handles all these different dialogues using [b]cases.[/b]
Each case has a different number, this way you can choose between different dialogues, or letting dialogues continue into another dialogue, but we will get to that part later.

First, let's create our first dialogue. 
Now this is where your creativity comes in. This is the time to start making up a story for your quest.
To give you an idea for a quest, I'm going to use some of my own dialogues.

In the method UpdateNPCChat(), add this after [b]switch (NpcDialogue) {[/b]
[code=java]
case 4: // Now I chose to make my first dialogue case 4, because I didn't have any other yet.
           // You might have to choose a different number
	talk("Oh dear, oh dear.. The king is going to kill me!", 605); // 605 is the NpcID, it will display the NPC's head
break;  // End of the case, this shows the game there is no more code to process in this case.

case 5: // This is the dialogue that will be shown after the player has clicked
           // Click here to continue on the dialogue of case 4.
	choice("Why? What's the matter?", "Though luck buddy.");
break;

case 6:
	talk2("I spilled some cheese on the castle court,","now there are rats everywhere!", 605);
 	// This method splits the text over two lines
	NpcDialogueSend = true; // I don't know why, but if you don't add this when using talk2(), the NPC's head will glitch
break;
[/code]

Now you're probably wondering "Choice? Huh?  Now what? How do I make it go to the correct dialogue now?!?".
No worries.
Open ClickingMost.java, and search for
[code=java]case 9157:[/code]

This case handles what happens when you click the first option in a dialogue.
In this case, so before the [b]break;[/b] add this:

[code]if(c.NpcDialogue == 5){ // This is the npcdialogue where the choice was given. As you can see, the number of the case is actually the number of the NpcDialogue.
	c.closeAll(); // This closes the current dialogue
	c.NpcDialogue = 6; // This opens up the dialogue with case number 6
	c.NpcDialogueSend = false; // This sends the new dialogue once
}[/code]

Now for the second option of the choice ("Tough luck buddy."), scroll down a bit in ClickingMost.java, to [b]case 9158[/b]
This case handles the second option of choices. In this case, add the following code.
This code will close the dialogue, and therefor end the conversation.

[code=java]case 9158:
	if(c.NpcDialogue == 5){ // If you have more dialogues that end the dialogue with the 2nd option of a choice, you can add them by using || c.NpcDialogue == ## with ## being the case number
		c.closeAll(); // This closes the current dialogue
	}
break;[/code]

Ok great, you can now make NpcDialogues with choices. But you still haven't even started the quest yet, neither have we added the dialogues to the NPC itself.
We also didn't add the dialogues to the sequence of dialogues.

But, let's continue with starting the quest first.
For this, we need to add two more dialogues.

Again, in the method UpdateNPCChat(), add these four cases.

[code=java]
case 8:
	talk2("Say, you look quite bold.", "Could you take care of the rats for me?", 605);
	NpcDialogueSend = true;
break;

case 9:
	choice("Yeah sure, but what's in it for me?","RATS?!? HELL NO MAN!");
break;

case 10:
	talk2("Come back to me when you have killed 5 rats,","I promise I will reward you greatly!", 605);
	quest1 = 1; // We have finally started the quest now.
	NpcDialogueSend = true;
break;

case 11:
	talk2("You killed 5 rats? Great!","Please, take this as a sign of gratitude.",605);
	quest1 = 3; // Finishes the quest
	NpcDialogueSend = true;
break;
[/code]

And in ClickingMost.java, add these pieces of code to handle the choices given.
In case 9157:
[code=java]
if(c.NpcDialogue == 9){
	c.closeAll();
	c.NpcDialogue = 10;
	c.NpcDialogueSend = false;
}[/code]

And in case 9158, add NpcDialogue == 9, so it would look like this:
[code=java]
if(c.NpcDialogue == 5 || c.NpcDialogue == 9){ 
	c.closeAll(); // This closes the current dialogue
}
break;
[/code]

Time for a little pat on the back. You have succesfully created all the neccesary dialogues, and choices.

Now it's time to add them to the NPC!


In Client.java, search for
[code=java]case 155:[/code]

This case handles the first option (besides Attack), of an NPC. In this case it will handle the option 'Talk'.
After:
[code=java]
if (!antiHax())
break;[/code]

Add this:
[code=java]
if(NPCID == 605 && quest1 == 0){ // If the player click the npc, and has not yet started the quest, it will open the first dialogue
	NpcDialogue = 4; // This is the first Dialogue
}
if(NPCID == 605 && quest1 == 2){ // If the player has killed all 5 rats, open the final dialogue
	NpcDialogue = 11; // Final dialogue before reward
}
[/code]


Now we will need to do one more thing to get the dialogues working, so bear with me, we this part is almost done!



Again, in Client.java, search for
[code=java]case 40:[/code]

This case handles the sequence of NpcDialogues.
You should probably see this:

[code=java]
if ( // Dialogues go here) {
	NpcDialogue += 1;
	NpcDialogueSend = false;
} else if (// Dialogues go here) {
	NpcDialogue = 0;
	NpcDialogueSend = false;
	RemoveAllWindows();
} else {
	closeInterface(); // This is used to close the interface incase an error occurs.
}[/code]

Depending on your source, there might already be dialogues there, but thats ok.

This:
[code=java]if ( // Dialogues go here) {
	NpcDialogue += 1;
	NpcDialogueSend = false;
}[/code]
part is used to go to the next dialogue after clicking on "Click here to continue".

This:
[code=java]else if (// Dialogues go here) {
	NpcDialogue = 0;
	NpcDialogueSend = false;
	RemoveAllWindows();
}[/code]
part is used to close the dialogue when clicking on "Click here to continue".


In the first part, we need to add the dialogues we want to continue.
Add the following dialogues:

[code=java]NpcDialogue == 4 || NpcDialogue == 6 || NpcDialogue == 7 || NpcDialogue == 8 || NpcDialogue == 11[/code]
 If there were already dialogues in your code, add  || infront of NpcDialogue == 4.

If you did it right, the first part of your code should now look like this:

[code=java]
if (NpcDialogue == 4 || NpcDialogue == 6 || NpcDialogue == 7 || NpcDialogue == 8 || NpcDialogue == 11) {
	NpcDialogue += 1;
	NpcDialogueSend = false;
}
[/code]

Now add the following dialogues to the second part of your code, so it looks like this.
[code]
else if (NpcDialogue == 10 || NpcDialogue == 12) {
	NpcDialogue = 0;
	NpcDialogueSend = false;
	RemoveAllWindows();
}[/code]
Again, if there were already dialogues in there, add || infront of NpcDialogue == 10.

Currently we do not have an NpcDialogue with case number 12 yet, but we will use it later for the quest reward.

You can be proud of yourself! If you did everything right you should now be able to talk to Sir Vyvin and start your quest.
Add the end of the tutorial I shall add the autospawn codes I used for this quest, so you can try it out yourself.
Ofcourse, you can also spawn him yourself if you want.

Alright, we have come far but we need to do a few more things. One thing we need to do is counting the specific NPC kills.




[b]Counting Specific NPC Kills[/b]

Ok great, Sir Vyvin gave us the order to kill 5 Rats. Now we need to know how to count how many rats we have killed.
Remember that variable Rats? It's time to put it to use.

Open up NpcHandler.java, and search for
[code=java]if ((temp != null) && !temp.disconnected) {[/code]
Anything below this code handles what happens when a player has killed an NPC. This is just what we need.

Below this piece of code, add this:
[code=java]
if ((npcs[i].npcType == 47) && (temp.quest1 == 1) && (temp.rats < 5)) {
	temp.rats += 1;
}[/code]

Now let's break this down.
[code=java]
temp = the client of the player
(npcs[i].npcType == 47) // This is the ID of the killed NPC. I used the NPC with ID 47, this is the small lvl 1 rat.
&& (temp.quest1 == 1)   // This means if the killed npc = id 47 and (&&) quest1 is equal to 1
&& (temp.rats < 5))       //  And the variable rats is smaller then 5 Then

temp.rats += 1;            //  Increase the value of the variable rats by 1
[/code]

Congratulations! You now know how to count specific NPC kills.

Now, in Client.java, find the method
[code=java]
public boolean process() {[/code]

And in it, add this code:
[code=java]
 if(quest1 == 1 && rats >= 5){
	quest1 = 2;
	sM("I have killed 5 rats, I should return to Sir Vyvin.");
}[/code]

This code checks if the player is currently working on the quest (quest1 == 1), and if he has killed enough rats (rats >=5).
If the player meets these requirements, quest1 gets set to 2, which enables the player to talk to Sir Vyvin again and recieve his reward.  He also gets to see a message so he knows he has killed enough rats.

Now remember what I said about NpcDialogue 12?  It's time to add it.

[b]Quest Rewards[/b]

In client.java, go back to
[code=java]case 40:[/code]

Below 
[code=java] else {
				closeInterface();
			}[/code]

Add this:

[code=java]
if (NpcDialogue == 12){
	// XP first, so the quest screen doesn't get f*cked up
	addSkillXP(500, playerAttack);  // Pretty obvious, adds 500 exp into attack strength and defence
	addSkillXP(500, playerStrength);
	addSkillXP(500, playerDefence);
	clearQuestInterface(); // Send a clean Quest Interface
	sendQuest("You have recieved:", 4911); // Second line of the quest interface
	sendQuest("You have completed *questnamehere*!", 4913); // Title
	sendQuest("Some steel items", 4914); // Line after "You have recieved"
	sendQuest("500 XP in Attack, Strength and Defence", 4915); // Next line
	sendQuest("2,500 Gold Pieces", 4916); // Next line
	showInterface(4909); // Send completed quest picture
	addItem(995,2500); // Gives 2500 GP
	addItem(1119, 1); // Gives a steel scimitar
	addItem(1069, 1); // Gives a steel platebody 
	addItem(1193, 1); // Steel platelegs
	addItem(1325, 1); // Steel kite
}
[/code]

Ofcourse you can add your own rewards and own texts.



